Soundness of a bounded linear-Diophantine solver. Given a, b > 0
and bounds a_max, b_max, 'solveLinearDiophantine a b c a_max b_max'
returns (found, x, y) where if found = True then a*x - b*y == c with
0 <= x <= a_max and 0 <= y <= b_max.

This benchmark asserts that *if* a witness (x0, y0) exists within
the stated bounds (i.e. c = a*x0 - b*y0 is achievable with bounded
nonnegative x0, y0), the solver actually finds some witness.

The implementation is the classical Bezout-based construction:
extended GCD, range-feasibility check via ceiling/floor division.
Difficulty: the unrolled extended Euclidean iteration produces a
deeply chained sequence of bitvector multiplications and signed
divisions, the bezout coefficients can be large (signed-extended to
4*k bits), and existence/non-existence depends on a nontrivial gcd
divisibility check.

Reference: appears in dependence analysis (loop nests), integer
programming, and the strides bitvector abstract domain.

The k = 8 variant has k-bit signed inputs and runs the inner eGCD
in 4*k bits with 4*k + 4 unrolled iterations.
